    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For those looking for the old multiline replace in inteliJ with version > 15.x. It seems somewhat hidden, but if you select multiple lines > click <code>CTRL+F</code>, then immediately click <code>CTRL+R</code> you are presented with the original multiline replace.</p>\n\n<p>This is working on Mac <code>IntelliJ 2016.1.3</code> with ⌘+F > ⌘+R</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/QgiEF.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/QgiEF.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2085257,
      "reputation" : 2569,
      "user_id" : 1856400,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/n3j33.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "spheenik",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1856400/spheenik"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1472130552,
    "creation_date" : 1472130552,
    "answer_id" : 39146260,
    "question_id" : 21219884,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>A clean approach would be to add <code>(?m)</code> in front of the regular expression, which turns on the multi line mode. This has the advantage that you can also use it in the global file search (Ctrl-Shift-F).</p>\n\n<p>Example: <code>(?m)\\{(.|\\n)*?\\}</code> searches for multi-line blocks surrounded by curly braces.</p>\n"
  }, {
